  "response": "The bar was a slice of twilight, a place where amber light pooled over worn wood and the hiss of a single, old piano played the same chords as the sea outside. Mara had slid into the corner booth, her hands wrapped around a glass of wine that tasted of late‑summer berries. The world outside the glass was a blur of streetlamps and shadows. Inside, the air smelled of cedar and a faint perfume that seemed to cling to the walls, a perfume that she could not quite name. She stared at the pool of liquid in her glass, waiting for something—a spark, a face, a word—to break the stillness.\n\nA man walked into the dimness. He moved like a whisper, and his presence seemed to draw the light into him. He wore a coat of black, the kind of coat that fell to his shoulders in soft folds, and his hair was a dark wave that caught the light with each subtle shift. When he took the seat beside her, the only thing he could have noticed was the way his gaze seemed to read her as if she were a page in a book. He was tall, his shoulders broad, and his smile was a crescent of something that might be warmth or a promise.\n\nHe slid a small, silver key onto her glass. It glinted like a piece of moonlit iron. The man’s hand was steady as it touched her elbow, fingers barely brushing the curve of her wrist. “Mara,” he said, the word soft, “I’ve been looking for you.”\n\nShe turned her head in his direction, and the world fell away except for his face—his eyes, black as the night, were liquid, deep, and in them she could see a reflection of her own pulse. The air around them seemed to thicken, as if the invisible breath of a storm were swirling at their feet.\n\nHe leaned in, and the moment stretched—a breath. He pressed his lips against her own. The contact was gentle, a kiss that was a caress of fire. The world narrowed to the feel of his lips, to the taste of his breath. Her chest swelled, and she could feel the tremor of something wild in her throat. She was at the edge of some